<td xpos="16" content="" csheight="290" align="left" height="290" valign="top" width="976"><font size="+1"><b>California Forest Fire Lookout sites, 506 active and abandoned sites listed. Table 1, Revised March 23, 2021.</b></font>
<p><font size="+1">Key to column headings: <b>ID</b> - A numerical count, <b>County</b> - The county the Lookout is in, <b>Topo Map</b> - The name of the 7.5 minute topographic map the Lookout is on, <b>Year</b> - Date of the map, <b>Lookout Name</b> - Name of active Lookout or inactive site, <b>LO</b> - Status of standing Lookout (see below), <b>EL, ft</b>. - Elevation in feet of the Lookout,<b> EL</b>
- How elevation is determined. BM = benchmark survey disk nearby. Spot
= spot elevation shown on the map. Inter. = No elevation shown so
interpreted from contours. <b>Latitude</b> - Degrees/Minute/Seconds NAD83,<b> Longitude</b> - Degrees/Minutes/Seconds NAD83, <b>Forest </b>- Name of National Forest Lookout is in, <b>Park or Other</b> - Other Land status, <b>Township</b> - Legal description of Lookout location, given as Township, Range, then Section number. Sometimes section number is unknown.</font></p>
<p><font size="+1"><b>Lookout Status Codes:</b>
A = structure in good condition, capable of being staffed. B =
Dilapidated and needs work, but standing. C = Badly damaged or falling
down. AS = usually staffed by Forest Service or CDF. AV = staffed by
volunteers. AR = A rental Lookout. A (LO site) is where the building
has been removed and there may be no evidence remaining, or it's status
may be unknown.</font></p>
<p><font size="+1">Fire lookouts may be Forest Service employees or volunteers, but they must possess <a href="http://ophthalmology.ucsf.edu/laser-vision-correction/lasik-frequently-asked-questions/" target="_top">excellent vision</a> to be able to survey the<br>
landscape for fires. A <a href="http://www.dellvision.com/" target="_top">Lasik Austin</a> eye examination can determine whether vision problems can be corrected by Lasik, especially the<br>
ability to see objects far in the distance, such as smoke from a forest fire.</font></p></td>
